# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
At first I was confused with this question since it is considered to be a DP problem, but I found that the DP solution was not very intuitive. For me it was much simpler and faster to solve this using greedy.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
At each position of the array, we are given a choice of either taking the steps from that point, or continuing with the steps we took previously. 

At the start, we know we have nums[0] steps, and hence our steps left should = nums[0].

As we traverse through the array, we update our steps left to be the maximum of (nums[index], stepsleft - 1), ensuring that we always have the most possible steps left. If we reach the last index, we know that we can reach the end and return true.

If we ever run out of steps, then we know we can't reach the last index and thus stop the loop and return false.
# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ --> 
- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public boolean canJump(int[] nums) {
        if(nums.length <= 1){
            return true;
        }
        int stepsleft = nums[0];
        int index = 1;
        while(stepsleft > 0){
            if (index == nums.length-1){
                return true;
            }
            stepsleft = Math.max(stepsleft-1, nums[index]);
            index++;
        }
        return false;
    }
}
```

