# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
You can found many Recursion with dp and tabulation solutions. But here we will discuss an ***very simple greedy solution that does not require any dynamic programming*** you just need a simple observation.

---

- Observation
for any index ***i*** in the given array, if i know the nearest index value (*let it be **x***) from where i can reach to my destination then the only thing i need to check now is that
Can i reach at index ***x*** from my current position (that is index ***i***)?.
->this question can easily answered by checking a condition is ***(i+nums[i]>=x)*** true?
{
here ***i+nums[i]*** -> the maximum distance(index value) that you can reach from ***i***th index. 
}
- if the above condition is true -> then we can easily reach to x from our current index i and so on our destination.
- if the above condition is false -> then we can't reach on our destination from our current index i.


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
n=size of the given vector nums
Our destination is ***n-1***th index.
- Basic Fact -> we can always reach at ***n-1***th index from ***n-1***th index itself irrespective of value in ***nums[n-1]***

- **Steps** :-

1) We will maintain a variable (***x***) that stores the value of nearest index from which we can reach at n-1th index and initialize it with ***n-1***.
2) We will also maintain a *bool variable* (***ans***) that stores the truth value that can we reach at our destination from the current index? (initialize ans with value 0).
2) Now We will start a for loop from ***i=n-1*** to ***i=0*** and for each i we do :
    - if we can reach at ***x*** from ***i*** then we assign ***ans=1*** and update value of x as ***x=i***
    - else assign ***ans=0***


4. Finally return the ans.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
***O(n)***
As we are Running a for loop from i=n-1 to i=0 So time complexity = O(n).
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
***O(1)***
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
/* Time coplexity = O(n) || Space complexity = O(1). */
    bool canJump(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n=nums.size();
        int x=n-1; //nearest variable from where we can reach (n-1)th index.(Greedy approach)
        bool ans=0;
        for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--)
        {
            if(i+nums[i]>=x) //condition that can we reach to x from i.
            {
                ans=1;
                x=i; // update the value of x as we got a nearer point.
            }
            else ans=0;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

```
